{"source_key":"sha256-31ae2543195c19275814384bf971ff26","record_index":1462,"record_hash":"sha256:819fb5bebc4df9164c8d02d3bedbf9de88fa1151496f506d456163cc36dbcbbb","timestamp":"2026-05-25T08:33:16.079Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Delete File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n*** Add File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n+# Maintainability Playbook\n+\n+Use this playbook for a focused cleanup pass after a feature or fix is working.\n+It is not a second spec. The implementation contract, product requirements, and\n+tests still win. The point is to make the code smaller, clearer, and easier for\n+the next maintainer to change.\n+\n+This works best for code that was built quickly, touched by agents, or grew a\n+little too much ceremony while the behavior was still moving.\n+\n+## Source Material\n+\n+Useful references behind this playbook:\n+\n+- [Google Engineering Practices: What to look for in a code review](https://google.github.io/eng-practices/review/reviewer/looking-for.html)\n+- [Rust API Guidelines checklist](https://rust-lang.github.io/api-guidelines/checklist.html)\n+- [GitHub: Review AI-generated code](https://docs.github.com/en/copilot/tutorials/review-ai-generated-code)\n+- [Martin Fowler: Code Smell](https://martinfowler.com/bliki/CodeSmell.html)\n+- [Refactoring Guru: Speculative Generality](https://refactoring.guru/smells/speculative-generality)\n+- [Claude Code best practices](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/best-practices)\n+- [Simon Willison: First run the tests](https://simonwillison.net/guides/agentic-engineering-patterns/first-run-the-tests/)\n+\n+## Specialize First\n+\n+Before reviewing, fill in the local facts for the subsystem in your head or in a\n+short note:\n+\n+- **Target:** the files, crate, package, service, or feature being reviewed.\n+- **Behavior contract:** what must stay true.\n+- **Primary entry points:** commands, routes, jobs, public APIs, or UI flows.\n+- **Owned boundaries:** modules that should own parsing, orchestration, storage,\n+  external calls, rendering, validation, or redaction.\n+- **Validation commands:** the narrow checks that prove this area still works.\n+- **Known non-goals:** cleanup that would become a redesign.\n+\n+Example:\n+\n+```text\n+Target: crates/foo/src/projection.rs\n+Contract: public output stays allowlisted and bounded\n+Entry point: foo::projection::project(...)\n+Boundaries: API request -> lookup -> domain projection -> serialization\n+Validation: cargo test -p foo projection && cargo clippy -p foo --all-targets --no-deps\n+Non-goal: replacing the storage model\n+```\n+\n+## What We Optimize For\n+\n+The code should feel intentionally authored, not like generated scaffolding.\n+\n+- It solves the problem we know exists now.\n+- Names are domain-specific and boring.\n+- Types carry meaning, but do not predict future product shape.\n+- Boundaries are obvious from reading the module names and call graph.\n+- Public surface area is no larger than the real caller needs.\n+- Tests encode behavior and intent, not incidental implementation details.\n+- Comments explain rationale, privacy, invariants, or tricky failure modes. They\n+  do not narrate the next line.\n+\n+## Review Passes\n+\n+Run these as separate passes. Preserve behavior unless you find a specific bug.\n+Prefer deleting or renaming over adding abstractions.\n+\n+### 1. Deletion Pass\n+\n+Look for speculative generality:\n+\n+- one-use traits, structs, modules, or helpers\n+- generic helpers with only one real caller\n+- parameters added for imagined future callers\n+- fields that are always `None`, always the same value, or only echoed back\n+- nested back-references already implied by structure\n+- comments that repeat the code\n+- tests that only lock in local shape\n+\n+Delete or inline when the call site becomes clearer.\n+\n+### 2. Naming Pass\n+\n+Rename vague concepts to the subsystem's domain.\n+\n+Prefer concrete names:\n+\n+- `ParsedRecord`\n+- `ProjectionRequest`\n+- `session_key`\n+- `source_record_hash`\n+- `write_session_update`\n+\n+Avoid framework fog unless the project already uses it meaningfully:\n+\n+- `Manager`\n+- `Processor`\n+- `Handler`\n+- `Adapter`\n+- `Service`\n+- `Provider`\n+- `Util`\n+- `Helper`\n+\n+Only use a generic name when there is a real shared concept across multiple\n+callers or implementations.\n+\n+### 3. Boundary Pass\n+\n+Write the intended shape as a small pipeline:\n+\n+```text\n+input boundary -> orchestration -> domain logic -> storage/external boundary -> output boundary\n+```\n+\n+Then check that each layer owns the right work:\n+\n+- CLI, HTTP, job, or UI parsing stays at the entry boundary.\n+- Repository, account, request, or environment resolution happens before domain\n+  logic.\n+- Parsing does not know persistence details.\n+- Persistence does not know provider-specific input vocabulary unless that is\n+  its job.\n+- Redaction, validation, permission checks, and serialization each have one\n+  obvious owner.\n+- Public/read projections do not leak raw storage keys, local paths, private\n+  payloads, or debug-only fields.\n+\n+If boundary cleanup requires moving large persistence or startup shapes,\n+document it instead of hiding a redesign inside a cleanup pass.\n+\n+### 4. Execution Trace Pass\n+\n+Follow one real invocation from entry point to side effect or output.\n+\n+At each boundary, write down:\n+\n+- which inputs are validated there\n+- which paths, IDs, refs, or names are normalized there\n+- which state is discovered there\n+- which values are converted to lossy strings there\n+- which side effects can happen there\n+- which errors the user would see first\n+\n+Look for:\n+\n+- the same input being normalized or rediscovered in two places\n+- expensive or side-effecting work before cheap local validation\n+- side effects before all relevant input validation\n+- two stored facts trying to describe the same source of truth\n+- path, ID, ref, or permission semantics changing between layers\n+- errors whose order no longer matches the user's invocation\n+\n+Fix only local issues discovered by the trace.\n+\n+### 5. API And Language Pass\n+\n+Scale this to the language and project.\n+\n+General checklist:\n+\n+- Keep items private by default.\n+- Public API should be only what real callers need.\n+- Prefer borrowed parameters when ownership is not needed.\n+- Avoid clones in loops unless ownership is genuinely required.\n+- Avoid typed errors until callers need to classify failures.\n+- Derive debug/eq/serialize traits only when they help diagnostics, tests, or\n+  the public contract.\n+- Avoid exposing raw internal IDs unless they are intentional handles.\n+- Keep transport DTOs at the boundary and map into domain types inside.\n+\n+Rust-specific checklist:\n+\n+- Prefer `pub(crate)` over `pub` inside a crate.\n+- Prefer `&str`, `&Path`, and slices for borrowed inputs.\n+- Use `anyhow` for CLI-owned/internal application crates unless consumers need\n+  typed error handling.\n+- Use `thiserror` or project error types only when API consumers match errors.\n+- Let `cargo clippy` find the boring stuff.\n+\n+### 6. Test Intent Pass\n+\n+Tests should answer: \"What behavior would break if a maintainer changed this?\"\n+\n+High-value tests usually cover:\n+\n+- malformed input handling\n+- idempotency or repeat runs\n+- incremental/growing input behavior\n+- privacy/redaction boundaries\n+- public API allowlists\n+- exact matching and fallback behavior\n+- truncation, pagination, or bounded output\n+- source-to-domain field extraction\n+\n+Avoid tests that only restate implementation structure, such as asserting\n+redundant parent handles inside nested objects unless that shape is the actual\n+contract.\n+\n+### 7. AI-Specific Review Pass\n+\n+Ask reviewers or subagents narrow questions:\n+\n+- What looks over-generalized for the problem we know exists?\n+- What would a maintainer misunderstand six months from now?\n+- Which name hides a concrete domain concept?\n+- Which public field is only present because it was easy to echo?\n+- Which test would still pass if the behavior were subtly wrong?\n+- Which helper, dependency, module, or DTO exists only because generated code\n+  tends to over-structure things?\n+- Which public field could leak private state, local paths, raw payloads, or\n+  debug vocabulary?\n+\n+Do not ask for a broad rewrite. The output should be small findings, not a new\n+architecture.\n+\n+## Cleanup Recipe\n+\n+### Step 0. Establish The Baseline\n+\n+Run the narrow checks before changing code. Use the project's real commands.\n+\n+Examples:\n+\n+```text\n+cargo fmt --check\n+cargo test -p <crate> <focused-test-name>\n+cargo check -p <crate-or-bin> --features <feature>\n+cargo clippy -p <crate> --all-targets --no-deps\n+pnpm test <package>\n+pnpm lint <package>\n+go test ./...\n+```\n+\n+If the baseline is already broken, fix or document that separately before\n+starting cleanup. A cleanup pass should not hide pre-existing failures.\n+\n+### Step 1. Main Agent Reads The Code\n+\n+The main agent should read the target code first:\n+\n+- entry point files\n+- orchestration files\n+- domain modules\n+- persistence/external-call modules\n+- serialization/projection/rendering modules\n+- nearby tests\n+\n+Then follow one concrete invocation through the subsystem. Keep this as a short\n+call-chain note, not a design document.\n+\n+Do not spawn subagents yet. The main agent needs enough context to judge whether\n+subagent feedback is useful or generic.\n+\n+### Step 2. Spawn Focused Review Subagents\n+\n+Use subagents for independent review, not implementation, at this stage. Give\n+each subagent a narrow lens and ask for findings only.\n+\n+Recommended subagents:\n+\n+- **Deletion reviewer:** find fake extensibility, one-use helpers, dead fields,\n+  ceremonial modules, and comments that repeat code.\n+- **Boundary reviewer:** check that entry parsing, orchestration, domain logic,\n+  persistence, external calls, redaction, and output stay separated.\n+- **Execution reviewer:** follow one real invocation and report duplicated\n+  normalization, surprising validation order, or side effects before validation.\n+- **API/language reviewer:** check visibility, error boundaries,\n+  ownership/cloning, naming, idioms, and public surface area.\n+- **Test reviewer:** check whether tests protect behavior and whether any tests\n+  are brittle implementation mirrors.\n+\n+Optional subagents:\n+\n+- **Security/privacy reviewer:** when public output, redaction, auth, local\n+  paths, tokens, or raw payloads changed.\n+- **Performance reviewer:** when parsing, rendering, storage, network calls, or\n+  hot loops changed.\n+- **Product-contract reviewer:** when output shape, copy, or user-facing flows\n+  changed.\n+\n+Do not ask subagents to rewrite files. Their output should be a short list of\n+high-signal findings with file/line references when possible.\n+\n+### Step 3. Triage Findings\n+\n+Merge feedback into three buckets:\n+\n+- **Fix now:** behavior risk, privacy risk, confusing boundary, or easy\n+  simplification.\n+- **Document only:** useful future concern but not cleanup-sized.\n+- **Ignore:** speculative architecture, taste-only renames, or changes that make\n+  the code larger.\n+\n+Be picky. A cleanup pass that accepts every suggestion becomes a rewrite.\n+\n+### Step 4. Make Small Behavior-Preserving Edits\n+\n+Edit in small groups:\n+\n+1. deletion and inlining\n+2. naming\n+3. visibility tightening\n+4. boundary cleanup\n+5. comment cleanup\n+6. test cleanup\n+\n+Run formatting after edits. Avoid mixing a behavior fix with broad cleanup\n+unless the behavior fix is tiny and directly discovered by the cleanup.\n+\n+### Step 5. Run Verification\n+\n+Run the focused checks again, then broaden only as needed.\n+\n+Examples:\n+\n+```text\n+cargo fmt --check\n+cargo test -p <crate>\n+cargo check -p <crate-or-bin> --features <feature>\n+cargo clippy -p <crate> --all-targets --no-deps\n+cargo machete\n+pnpm test <package>\n+pnpm lint <package>\n+```\n+\n+If dependencies changed, run the dependency cleanup/checker for the ecosystem.\n+\n+### Step 6. Optional Second Review\n+\n+After edits, spawn one or two fresh subagents only if the diff is non-trivial.\n+\n+Good second-pass prompts:\n+\n+- \"Review only the cleanup diff. Did behavior accidentally change?\"\n+- \"Look for new complexity introduced by the cleanup.\"\n+- \"Check whether any tests became weaker or more implementation-coupled.\"\n+- \"Check whether public output now leaks less than before.\"\n+\n+Avoid repeating the full review unless the cleanup touched many modules.\n+Re-review has diminishing returns.\n+\n+### Step 7. Summarize The Result\n+\n+The final summary should say:\n+\n+- what was removed or clarified\n+- whether behavior changed\n+- what validation ran\n+- what suggestions were deliberately skipped and why\n+- any remaining tradeoffs\n+\n+Do not claim the code is now future-proof. The win is that it is smaller and\n+clearer now.\n+\n+## Validation Habit\n+\n+Before and after cleanup, run the narrow checks for the target area. For\n+behavior-neutral cleanup, the best result is boring: smaller code, clearer\n+names, and the same behavior passing.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-25T08:33:16.079Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}